{{Orphan|date=August 2014}}
'''Healthcare CRM''', also known as Healthcare Relationship Management <ref>http://www.zdnet.com/article/can-software-solve-our-healthcare-crisis/</ref>, is a broadly used term for a [[Customer relationship management]] system, or [[Customer relationship management|CRM]], used in healthcare. There are two basic types of healthcare [[Customer relationship management|CRM]]s, one is for a healthcare organization to stay in contact with their patients, the other is for a healthcare organization to stay in contact with referring organizations.
The reason that there are two types of healthcare CRMs is because healthcare organizations generate new patients in two different ways. The first way is from patient choice. Individuals who are sick, hurt, need a dentist, or need a healthcare provider in some way find one that is suitable to their needs themselves. Healthcare organizations want to attract new patients or maintain repeating patients so they use a healthcare CRM to manage the relationships with the public. This might be tasks like sending checkup appointment reminders, or birthday cards.<ref name=Oracle>{{cite web|last=Oracle|first=Products|title=Oracle data sheet|url=http://www.oracle.com/us/products/applications/siebel/047088.pdf|publisher=Oracle|accessdate=14 February 2013}}</ref>
The second way healthcare organizations generate patients is by referring organizations. If an individual goes to a dentist and that individual needs their wisdom teeth removed, the dentist might refer that patient to an oral surgeon. Many hospitals and other specialty clinics rely heavily on referrals for patients. Hospitals and specialty clinics use a healthcare CRM to maintain relationships with primary care physicians or other referring healthcare organizations.<ref name="MarketWare Systems">{{cite web|last=MarketWare|first=Systems|title=Healthcare CRM|url=http://marketware.com/|publisher=MarketWare|accessdate=14 February 2013}}</ref>
A healthcare-specific CRM differs from traditional CRM systems mainly in three ways<ref>http://www.clpmag.com/2017/07/building-relationships/</ref>: # Healthcare CRM systems are built to work within a healthcare organization’s unique structure. For example, a generic CRM system assumes that all people it stores will only be associated with one organization at any given time, yet physicians often work across multiple healthcare institutions. Generic CRM systems require significant customization to meet the needs of healthcare organizations<ref>https://www.hc1.com/platform/features/healthcare-crm/</ref>. # Healthcare CRM systems automatically unify and harmonize data from Laboratory Information Systems (LIS), billing, supply, courier, payer and other sources. Generic CRM systems expect significant manual entry of tasks and opportunities on the part of healthcare workers. # Healthcare CRM systems are designed to be HIPPA compliant, with secure collaboration to support healthcare requirements.
There are a few companies that offer healthcare CRMs these are the industry leaders for the two types of healthcare CRMs.<ref name=tuOtempO>{{cite web|last=tuOtempO|first=Solutions|title=CRM for healthcare|url=http://www.tuotempo.com|publisher=tuOtempO|accessdate=1 July 2013}}</ref>
